#Text=Name a Star
#Text=If you were interested in naming a star after yourself or someone you know , several companies offer services to name your own star .
#Text=Note that the star wo n't be the official name of the star and it 's likely that the star has already been named something else in another registry .
#Text=While the name wo n't be official , you 'll receive a certificate and other astronomical gifts that will make you or someone you know feel special .
#Text=Officially , most stars have already been cataloged with a series of letters and numbers .
#Text=However , larger , more significant stars usually have a unique name given to them by different cultures or astronomers .
#Text=Steps
#Text=Naming a Star Online
#Text=Search online for star-naming registries .
#Text=Several non-official , for-profit online registries offer star naming services .
#Text=These registries give you a certificate for your star and other items like photographs of constellations , a star map , fact sheets , and space-themed accessories .
#Text=Most packages will also include instructions on how to find your star in the sky .
#Text=Look online at different companies and compare what they offer to help narrow down your decision .
#Text=The only official registry is the International Astronomical Union ( IAU ) .
#Text=They define how stars and other celestial bodies are officially named for astronomical and scientific purposes .
#Text=Compare gift packages and choose the one you like the best .
#Text=Most online star-naming registries will have different packages that you can buy .
#Text=If you want to get more merchandise , you ’ll have to purchase a more expensive package .
#Text=Look at the different packages and choose one based on your budget and what they have to offer .
#Text=Star naming packages typically cost anywhere from $ 30 to $ 100 .
#Text=Purchase the star and wait for your certificate to come in the mail .
#Text=Once you select the package , input your payment details and put in your order .
#Text=Once you pay , you ’ll be prompted to type in your desired star name .
#Text=Most companies will then pick out a star for you and show you a photo of it in relation to other stars .
#Text=If you ’re naming a star after someone else , you should input their address so that the package gets delivered to them .
#Text=You should receive an email confirmation and a receipt for your purchase .
#Text=Email the IAU to officially name unnamed comets or meteors .
#Text=Though most stars , constellations , and planets have already been named , new comets or meteors typically receive a name based on the person who discovered them .

#Text=If you have a telescope and see a comet or meteor that you do n’t think was named yet , email cbatiau@eps.harvard.edu. As you track the comet or meteor , make sure to keep meticulous records and contact the IAU as soon as possible .
#Text=In the email , include your name , address , contact details , date and time of the observation , the observation method , and the observation site .
#Text=When a comet can be seen by the naked eye , you typically can not name it since many other people “ discovered ” it at the same time .
#Text=The observation method could include a telescope , naked eye , or photograph .
#Text=The observation site should include the town or city name and longitude and latitude of your location when you made the discovery .
#Text=Usually astronomers and teams of astronomers with telescopes are the first ones to find and name new comets and meteors .
#Text=Thinking Of a Good Name
#Text=Name a star after someone you know for a thoughtful gift .
#Text=Most people will name a star after someone they know as a gift .
#Text=Again , while the star may not be officially named across all registries , the merchandise that you get with the package is a great gift for someone interested in astronomy .
#Text=Having a star named after you will leave most people feeling happy and unique .
#Text=You can also name a star after someone who has passed away in honor of their name .
#Text=You can also name the star after yourself .
#Text=Think of a name from ancient mythology for a historical approach .
#Text=Most stars and constellations have been historically named based on characters from ancient mythology .
#Text=Some stars and constellations may have more than 1 name depending on the culture or society that originally coined their names .
#Text=For example , Taurus was originally named Ain in the original Arabic text .
#Text=Constellations named using Greek mythology include Andromeda , Draco , and Orion .
#Text=Name a star by its size and constellation for an official name .
#Text=Officially , most stars are named by their constellation so astronomers can keep track of them .
#Text=Usually , the stars will have a designation after the constellation name like alpha or beta to describe their size .
#Text=For example , the largest star in the Orion constellation is named Alpha Orionis and the second largest star is called Beta Orionis .
#Text=Alpha , beta , and gamma come from the Greek alphabet .
#Text=This method of naming stars is called the Bayer method .
#Text=Discover a new star and name it after yourself .
#Text=When new stars are discovered they are named after the person or team who discovered them along with coordinates of the star .
#Text=Astronomers or teams of astronomers with high-powered telescopes are typically the ones who discover new stars .

#Text=These official names are cataloged by the International Astronomical Union and have names like Luyten 726-8A , BD +5deg 1668 , and Kruger 60 A. It is highly unlikely that the star you find has n't been cataloged but if you believe that you 've found a new star , email cbatiau@eps.harvard.edu and include details like the time you discovered the star , your name , address , and contact information .
#Text=There 's a good chance the star that you found has already been discovered .
#Text=You can cross-reference the IAU constellation and star catalogs to see whether the coordinates of your star match an already existing star .
#Text=The coordinates are calculated by determining the star 's ascension and declination in space , which is the equivalent to longitude and latitude on earth .
#Text=There are millions of stars that have already been cataloged by the International Astronomical Union .
#Text=Do n't pick a name you do n't like .
#Text=If you keep getting trapped by two names , put them together .
#Text=Quick Summary
